{
  "_comment": [
    "What this shows: two independent scenarios that each require address-range",
    "link endpoints.  Separate source/destination view pairs keep the two",
    "scenarios visually distinct — one per row in the rendered diagram.",
    "",
    "Scenario 1 — partial source fraction, full target view (top row):",
    "  'from' selects the upper half of Zone 1 using an address range",
    "  [0x00018000, 0x00020000]. Zone 1 starts at 0x00010000, so 0x00018000",
    "  is a mid-section address — not a section boundary. No section ID can",
    "  name this fraction, so the address-range form is the correct tool.",
    "  'to' omits 'sections', anchoring to the full expanded detail view.",
    "",
    "Scenario 2 — named source section, partial target range (bottom row):",
    "  'from' uses the section ID 'unit_1'. 'to' selects [0x40011000, 0x4001B000]",
    "  in dst_b: a range that starts mid-Sub 0 and ends mid-Sub 2, crossing",
    "  three sub-blocks without covering any one completely and without spanning",
    "  the full expanded view. A section-ID list cannot express this mid-section",
    "  range; the address-range form is required on the 'to' side.",
    "",
    "Names are neutral placeholders, not a real chip map."
  ],
